The Point of Information to the Speaker serves to ask the Speaker a question regarding their speech. It may only be raised after the Delegate has finished speaking and when the Speaker opens himself to Points of Information. The Speaker may open himself to:
\n(a)	any and all Points of Information;
\n(b)	a specified maximum number of Points of Information;
\n(c)	no Points of Information.
\n\nThe Point of Information to the Speaker should have the form of a question. A short introductory statement may precede the question. It shall only refer to the discussed matter. The Speaker may choose not to answer the Point of Information. Dialogue on the floor is not allowed. To ask a follow-up question, the Delegate must first ask for a permission of the Chair.

Amendments may be used to: 
(a)add a clause to the Resolution. The Amendments shall include the exact text to be added. Clauses are always added to the end of the Resolution; 
(b) modify a clause. The Amendment shall cite the section to be modified and include the exact modified text; 
(c) strike a clause. The Amendment shall cite the section to be struck.


Amendments must be submitted on Amendment sheets provided by a Chairs’ Assistant. They shall be read by the Chair before they can be debated upon. A Chair may refuse to debate upon an Amendment on the grounds that it is too similar to a previous Amendment that has failed to pass.
